TY  - JOUR
AB  - This paper demonstrates a tradeoff between the
                                                risk-shifting and hedging incentives of firms and
                                                identifies conditions under which each dominates. A
                                                firm may have the incentive to hedge in a
                                                multi-period context, even if no such incentive
                                                exists in a single-period one. Unrestricted access
                                                to swaps in the presence of asymmetric information
                                                about firm type and the swapping motive would lead
                                                to unbounded speculation resulting in breakdowns in
                                                swap and debt markets. Price-based methods are
                                                unable to control this and market makers have to
                                                rely upon additional exposure information or credit
                                                enhancement devices to preserve equilibrium.
